entry.title: ui: add accelerator registration to WebDialogDelegate
entry.content:
Currently, the only way to register accelerators is to override

GetAccelerators() and AcceleratorPressed(). There are two clients that

do this - one registers a single accelerator, the other registers about

a dozen. It would be good if it was possible to use WebDialogDelegate

and have accelerators without extending it, and ultimately allow for

less subclasses of this class.



This change adds a new method called RegisterAccelerator() to

WebDialogDelegate, and adds an internal accelerator table to

WebDialogDelegate. It also adds default logic to the class to use that

table to implement GetAccelerators() and AcceleratorPressed(). Future

CLs will migrate both existing clients to RegisterAccelerator(), then

remove GetAccelerators() and AcceleratorPressed() and remove both the

current client subclasses that override these methods.

entry.title: Revert "Exclude HeuristicSource::kLegacy from non-active patterns"
entry.content:
This reverts commit 440828a02e56dcecd43896676a0c765db907c3b9.



Reason for revert: Likely culprit of failing autofill tests, e.g. https://ci.chromium.org/ui/p/chrome/builders/ci/linux-chromeos-chrome/37601



Original change's description:

> Exclude HeuristicSource::kLegacy from non-active patterns

>

> A HeuristicSource describes a mechanism to get heuristic predictions,

> which is currently either ML or regexes. Due to pattern provider,

> which can provide different regex definitions, "regexes" is split

> further into different PatternSources.

>

> The active HeuristicSource defines the mechanism that's used to compute

> the fields' heuristic types used in production (the one that will

> influence the overall type used for filling).

>

> The non-active HeuristicSources are defined as the set of all available

> HeuristicSources, except the active HeuristicSource. The PatternSources

> among these non-active HeuristicSources are used to compute shadow predictions for the kAutofillParsingPatternProvider experiment.

>

> What exactly all available HeuristicSources are depends on build flags

> and feature flags, and this CL changes that definition.

>

> Generally:

> - HeuristicSource::kMachineLearning is only available when

> kAutofillModelPredictions is enabled.

> - HeuristicSource::kDefault, HeuristicSource::kExperimental and

> HeuristicSource::kNextGen are only available in Chrome branded builds

> when kAutofillParsingPatternProvider is enabled.

> - HeuristicSource::kLegacy is always available.

>

> This CL removes HeuristicSource::kLegacy from the available patterns in

> Chrome branded builds when kAutofillParsingPatternProvider is enabled.

> This is desirable for a few reasons:

> - Chrome branded builds with kAutofillParsingPatternProvider are not

entry.title: Allow anyone to review updates to the non-inclusive language list
entry.content:
Because this list must be updated when importing third-party libraries

and they frequently use language that trips up our PRESUMBIT checks,

third-party library updates often get blocked on requiring an infra

review.



The inclusive language presubmit is excellent, and reviewers should

certainly question if authors are adding exceptions in 1st party code,

but we don't need an infra review for that too. The PRESUBMIT guides

folks to the right path (change your language use) and reviews of the

CL will see if they are not.



Mostly people seem to currently just bypass hooks when the need to

update this file, as seen by the fact that every time I update the

file there's a ton of other unrelated changes. Bypassing presubmit

hooks has other negative impacts as it can cause people to commit

code that should be rejected by other hooks as well.



So this CL lowers the friction to updating the non-incluslive

language list so that any reviewer can approve it.

entry.title: [DBSC] Trigger /ListAccounts on session termination
entry.content:
Session binding impacts signed in accounts on the web. If the session is

terminated on the client, the user will be signed out as soon as the

short lived cookies expire. This might lead to inconsistency between

accounts in chrome and in the web.



To achieve consistency, /ListAccounts is triggered on session

termination. On a follow-up CL, short lived cookies should be deleted

before /ListAccounts call to ensure it detects inconsistency.

entry.title: Don't create Autofill ML model handler without an optimization_guide
entry.content:
See crbug.com/1506768#c3 why this is necessary. Ideally, this should be

as simple as adding a check in AutofillMlPredictionModelServiceFactory::

BuildServiceInstanceForBrowserContext(). However, like this [1] comment

mentions, the functions is not supported to return null*. So like the

comment suggests, the check is placed in GetBrowserContextToUse()

instead.



AutofillMlPredictionModelServiceFactory is a ProfileKeyedServiceFactory,

which marks its override of GetBrowserContextToUse() as final. To

circumvent that, this CL makes AutofillMlPredictionModelServiceFactory a

BrowserContextKeyedServiceFactory instead. This is a no-op, since the

logic actually redirect to the main profile in every case (i.e. it

doesn't need to distinguish by Chrome profile).



* I guess except if allocation for the std::unique_ptr<> fails?

entry.title: Add helpers for resolving *-position for BackgroundImageGeometry
entry.content:

a *-position value to an "absolute" value - applying the edge affinity

etc. This keeps the knowledge in a single location. Convert current uses

are not mixed when computing positions. In some cases - no-repeat - the

edge affinity used snapped/unsnapped while any percentages were resolved

using snapped. This may lead to (likely minor) differences in rendering.

entry.title: Exclude HeuristicSource::kLegacy from non-active patterns
entry.content:
A HeuristicSource describes a mechanism to get heuristic predictions,

which is currently either ML or regexes. Due to pattern provider,

which can provide different regex definitions, "regexes" is split

further into different PatternSources.



The active HeuristicSource defines the mechanism that's used to compute

the fields' heuristic types used in production (the one that will

influence the overall type used for filling).



The non-active HeuristicSources are defined as the set of all available

HeuristicSources, except the active HeuristicSource. The PatternSources

among these non-active HeuristicSources are used to compute shadow predictions for the kAutofillParsingPatternProvider experiment.



What exactly all available HeuristicSources are depends on build flags

and feature flags, and this CL changes that definition.



Generally:

- HeuristicSource::kMachineLearning is only available when

kAutofillModelPredictions is enabled.

- HeuristicSource::kDefault, HeuristicSource::kExperimental and

HeuristicSource::kNextGen are only available in Chrome branded builds

when kAutofillParsingPatternProvider is enabled.

- HeuristicSource::kLegacy is always available.



This CL removes HeuristicSource::kLegacy from the available patterns in

Chrome branded builds when kAutofillParsingPatternProvider is enabled.

This is desirable for a few reasons:

- Chrome branded builds with kAutofillParsingPatternProvider are not

using the kLegacy patterns, not even for shadow metrics. They are

intended to be lower-quality regexes for non-Chrome branded builds.

- Since they are currently part of the non-active HeuristicSources,

they take up additional computational resources during parsing.



Bug: 1479353

entry.title: Remove incorrect CHECK() in ProfileTokenQuality
entry.content:
ProfileTokenQuality::GetObservationTypeFromField(field) is called at

submission and receives a field with autofill_source_profile_guid() set,

meaning that the field was autofilled with the profile of GUID

*autofill_source_profile_guid() at some point before. The logic

distinguishes between two cases:

- field.is_autofilled is true: The user accepted the autofilled value as

is.

- field.is_autofilled is false: The user edited the field since it was

filled with the aforementioned profile.



In the second case, the code currently CHECK()s that

field.previously_autofilled() is true. This serves simply as

"documentation" what this case is about, but is not relied upon in any

way. However, it turns out that this CHECK() is not guaranteed:

- When the user manually edits a field, BAM::OnTextFieldDidChangeImpl()

sets the field's is_autofilled to false and also updates its

previously_autofilled property. In this case, the CHECK() works fine.

- When Javascript modifies the value,

BAM::OnJavaScriptChangedAutofilledValueImpl() is called instead. In

this case, neither is_autofilled nor previously_autofilled are

changed. (see crbug.com/1506559)

At form submission, is_autofilled is still false though, since it is

reextracted from Blink. Since previously_autofilled is not stored in

Blink, it remains false, causing the CHECK() to fail.



Ultimately, this is a bug in the behavior of previously_autofilled.

Changing it is not trivial though, since a lot of metrics rely on it.



For now, to unblock the ProfileTokenQuality rollout, this CL simply

removes the CHECK().



Fixed: 1506195

entry.title: Fix progress function calculation
entry.content:
We can simplify the progress function when either all the operands

resolve to the same canonical unit or all the operands have the same type.

Currently `progress(10em from 10em to 100em)` crashes as we try to compute the canonical value in either case of simplification.



This CL changes this behavior to distinguish which simplification path

to use, so that in the mentioned progress() example we just take the

double values when all the operands are of the same type.
